es, no longer suffice as an intellectual framework. Jerome McGann proposes we look instead to philology--a discipline which has been out of fashion for many decades but which models the concerns of digital humanities with surprising fidelity. For centuries, books have been the best way to preserve and transmit knowledge. But as libraries and museums digitize their archives and readers abandon paperbacks for tablet computers, digital media are replacing books as the repository of cultural memory. While both the mission of the humanities and its traditional modes of scholarship and critical study are the same, the digital environment is driving disciplines to work with new tools that require major, and often very difficult, institutional changes. Now more than ever, scholars need to recover the theory and method of philological investigation if the humanities are to meet their perennial commitments. Textual and editorial scholarship, often marginalized as a narrowly technical domain, should be made a priority of humanists' attention.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCommunication in learning and scholarshipxTechnological innovations. 0aDigital mediaxSocial aspects. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspects. 0aHumanitiesxResearch. 0aHumanitiesxStudy and teaching. 0aInternetxSocial aspects. 0aLearning and scholarshipxSocial aspects. 0aMemoryxSocial aspects. 0aSocial change. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Hermeneutics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067436924540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674369245423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674369245.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles